Imagine a very long webpage with a lot of sections (i.e., an HTML specification on one page). When a user requests a specific section (e.g. page.html#section7), how about the web server streams this section first and then the other sections?
Stream sequence:
1. The beginning of the HTML document up to <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for section 1, 2, 3 etc.
Then the browser would ensure that sections 1 to 6 are displayed above section 7 on the webpage.
Does that make sense? Would that be helpful?
The linked section (#section7) should be rendered as quickly as possible without having to implement elements with JavaScript again. I simply want to have an extra long HTML document, but the linked sections should be rendered as quickly as possible. This should work with HTML.
The content could be streamed, and then the browser would insert all <contents> into the <div>.
<div id="sec1"></div>
<div id="sec2"></div>
and so on.
<div id="sec7">section 7…</div>
<contents for="sec1">section 1…</contents>
<contents for="sec2">section 2…</contents>
usw.
Es would not be streamed in order, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it had been streamed in order.
@user22 You can reorder documents like that without JS as well. You should not use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string search parameters so that the server knows which section you want to display first. When reordering the parts, you have several options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use a template with sections
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual sequence (what the user sees) does not match the DOM sequence. It would be useful to have an HTML function that allows for non-sequential streaming, but the browser would then arrange the content in the DOM sequence.
But the idea with slots looks promising. I'll try that.
@user22 Oh, do you want the browser to put the DOM sequence in order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first, only so the user can see it as quickly as possible. If that could work without affecting the DOM sequence, that would be great, then the browser would take care of making the resulting DOM sequence match the visual sequence.
So, Section 7 should be streamed first, but the final result should look as if all sections were streamed in sequence.
@user22 @user23 Check out PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
